1.4:
A nation rotted through with sin!
A people staggering under their own guilt —
offspring of wrongdoers, children schooled in destruction!
They have walked away from Yahweh;
they have treated the Holy One of Israel with contempt;
they have turned their backs and gone.

1.5:
Why keep inviting the blow? Why go on rebelling?
From head to heart — the whole body is sick;
from crown to core — everything has given way.

1.23:
Your officials are rogues — thieves' accomplices, every one.
They are all greedy for bribes;
they race after their cut.
The orphan gets no hearing;
the widow's complaint never reaches their ears.

2.9:
So human beings are being bent down;
every person is being brought low.
Do not lift them up!

2.11:
The proud gaze of humanity will be brought to the ground;
human arrogance will be flattened —
and Yahweh alone will stand high on that day.

2.17:
Human arrogance will be bent to the ground;
human pride will be leveled —
and Yahweh alone will be raised high on that day.

5.25:
Therefore the burning anger of Yahweh flared against his own people;
he reached out his hand against them and struck —
and the mountains themselves shook.
Their corpses lay strewn in the streets like refuse.
And still — for all of this — his anger has not turned back;
his hand is still raised to strike again.

5.29:
They roar like a lion, like young lions they snarl;
they spring on the prey, drag it away —
and there is no one to rescue it.

8.12:
Do not cry 'Conspiracy!' every time they do.
Do not fear what they fear;
do not be in dread.

8.13:
Set apart Yahweh of hosts as the one who is holy —
let him be your fear,
let him be your dread.

9.17:
Therefore the Lord takes no delight in their young men,
shows no mercy to their orphans and widows —
for every one of them is profane, a doer of evil,
every mouth full of senseless words.
Yet for all of this, his anger is not spent;
his hand is still raised to strike.

9.19:
By the fury of Yahweh of hosts the land is scorched;
the people themselves become the fire's own fuel —
not one man spares his brother.

9.20:
They grab on the right and still go hungry;
they devour on the left and are not satisfied —
each one consuming the flesh of those closest to him.

11.6:
The wolf will live beside the lamb;
the leopard will bed down with the young goat;
calf and lion cub and fatted beast together —
and a small child will be their keeper.

11.7:
Cow and bear grazing in the same field;
their calves and cubs sleeping side by side.
Even the lion will eat straw like an ox.

11.8:
A nursing baby playing at the cobra's hole;
a weaned toddler reaching into the adder's den —
and neither will come to harm.

11.10:
In that day the Root of Jesse will stand up as a signal-banner for all the peoples;
the nations will come seeking him,
and the place where he dwells will be radiant with glory.

19.3:
Egypt's spirit will drain away;
I will confound their strategy —
they will turn in desperation to idols, sorcerers, mediums, and spiritists.

19.4:
I will surrender Egypt into the grip of a harsh master;
a ruthless king will rule over them —
so declares the Lord, Yahweh of hosts.

19.6:
The river channels will turn foul;
the Nile's many branches will shrink and dry;
reeds and rushes will wither away.

19.13:
Zoan's princes have made themselves fools;
Memphis's princes are utterly deceived;
the chiefs of Egypt's clans have led the whole country astray.

19.22:
Yahweh will strike Egypt — strike and then heal.
They will turn back to Yahweh;
he will hear their plea and heal them.

19.25:
whom Yahweh of hosts will bless, declaring:
'Blessed be Egypt, my people;
Assyria, the work of my hands;
and Israel, my inheritance.'

13.3:
I have called out my consecrated ones by name;
my mighty warriors are assembled for the work of my anger —
those who take fierce joy in my supremacy.

13.8:
Anguish seizes them — the pangs of a woman in hard labour.
They look at one another in disbelief;
their faces blaze with terror.

13.10:
The stars of heaven go dark — constellations and all.
The sun rises in darkness;
the moon withholds its light.

13.12:
Survivors will be rarer than pure gold —
rarer than Ophir's finest ore;
what was common will become priceless.

13.16:
Their children will be smashed to death before their eyes;
their homes stripped bare;
their wives taken by force.

13.18:
Their arrows will mow down the young men;
no mercy on the newborn,
no pity in their eyes for children.

13.21:
Desert jackals will laze in the ruins;
the empty palaces will echo with screech owls.
Ostriches will nest there;
wild goats will leap among the fallen stones.

13.22:
Wolves will howl from the towers;
jackals will fill the pleasure palaces with their cries.
Her end is almost here — her days will not stretch out.

14.13:
In your heart you made these boasts:
'I will storm the heavens;
I will set my throne above the very stars of God;
I will sit on the mount of the divine assembly,
enthroned at the northern heights of the cosmos —'

15.3:
In every street sackcloth is all they wear;
on every rooftop, in every open square —
weeping, wailing, tears running free.

15.4:
The shout from Heshbon and Elealeh carries all the way to Jahaz;
at the sound even Moab's own soldiers cry out —
every soul within them trembling.

16.1:
Send the tribute lamb to the ruler of the land —
from Sela, across the desert road,
to the mount of Daughter Zion.

16.3:
'Give us your counsel — act justly!
Let your shadow fall like midnight at noon;
hide the scattered outcasts;
do not give away the fugitive —'

16.4:
'Let my scattered people settle with you —
be their cover against the destroyer.
For the tyrant is finished;
the devastation is done;
the one who ground people underfoot is gone from the land.'

16.7:
So let Moab mourn for Moab — all of it, mourning.
Cry for the delicacies of Kir-hareseth;
groan with real grief.

17.7:
In that day — stripped of everything —
people will turn their gaze to the One who made them;
their eyes will find the Holy One of Israel.

17.8:
He will not go back to the altars his own hands built;
he will not look to what his fingers made —
no more Asherim, no more incense shrines.

30.8:
Now go — write it before them on a tablet;
carve it into a scroll
so it stands as a witness for future days, forever.

26.4:
Trust in Yahweh — trust him forever —
for Yah, Yahweh himself,
is the everlasting Rock.

26.5:
He brings down the proud who dwell in high places;
the lofty city he levels —
down to the ground, down to the dust.

26.14:
They are dead — they will not live;
the shades of the dead will not rise.
You punished and erased them;
every memory of them is gone.

27.3:
I, Yahweh, am its keeper;
I water it at every moment.
So that nothing can harm it, I guard it night and day.

27.6:
In coming days Jacob will take deep root;
Israel will blossom and bud
and fill the whole wide world with fruit.

28.20:
The bed is too short to lie on;
the blanket too narrow to wrap yourself in.
Every arrangement you made to protect yourself will fail.

32.9:
Rise up, you women who are at ease —
listen to my voice;
you complacent daughters, pay attention to what I am saying.

32.12:
Beat your breasts in mourning
for the fertile fields,
for the pleasant vineyards,
for the fruitful vines.

32.17:
The fruit of righteousness will be peace;
the harvest of righteousness —
quietness and confident security, forever.

33.7:
Look — their brave warriors
cry out in the open streets;
the peace envoys are weeping bitterly.

33.9:
The earth mourns and fades;
Lebanon is shamed and withers;
Sharon has become a desert;
Bashan and Carmel shake off their leaves.

33.10:
'Now I will rise,' declares Yahweh.
'Now I will be exalted;
now I will be lifted high.'

33.11:
You conceive nothing but chaff;
you give birth to stubble —
your own breath will be the fire that consumes you.

33.13:
Hear — all you who are far away —
hear what I have done;
and you who are near — acknowledge my power.

33.16:
that one will dwell on the heights;
his refuge will be a stronghold of rock.
His bread will be given to him;
his water will never run dry.

33.22:
For Yahweh is our judge;
Yahweh is our lawgiver;
Yahweh is our king —
he will save us.

37.25:
'I dug wells and drank wherever I pleased;
with the sole of my foot I drained
every stream in Egypt.'

44.26:
'who confirms every word my servant has spoken,
who carries out every plan my messengers have declared —
who says of Jerusalem: it will be lived in again;
who says of the cities of Judah: they will be rebuilt;
who says of their ruins: I will raise them up,'

40.10:
See — the Lord Yahweh comes in strength;
his arm holds the power.
Look — he carries his reward with him;
his recompense goes before him.

41.2:
Who roused that conqueror from the east
and summoned victory to meet him at every step?
He delivers nations before him;
kings fall beneath his feet.
His sword makes them dust;
his bow scatters them like driven stubble.

41.5:
The coastlands saw it and trembled;
the ends of the earth shook with fear.
They drew near and came.

41.16:
You will winnow them;
the wind will carry them away,
the gale will scatter them.
Then you will rejoice in Yahweh;
you will glory in the Holy One of Israel.

42.3:
A bent reed he will not snap;
a guttering wick he will not snuff out.
He will carry out justice faithfully.

52.9:
Burst into song together, you ruins of Jerusalem —
for Yahweh has comforted his people;
he has redeemed Jerusalem.

57.13:
Cry out then — let your crowd of idols save you!
The wind will carry them all away;
a single breath will scatter them.
But the one who takes refuge in me —
he will possess the land;
he will inherit my holy mountain.

60.4:
Lift your eyes — look around — they are all gathering, all coming to you.
Your sons are coming from far away;
your daughters are being carried on the hip.

61.2:
to proclaim the year of Yahweh's favor —
and the day of vengeance of our God —
to comfort all who mourn;

61.10:
I will greatly rejoice in Yahweh;
my whole self will exult in my God —
for he has clothed me with the garments of salvation;
he has wrapped me in the robe of righteousness,
as a bridegroom crowns himself with a garland,
as a bride adorns herself with jewels.

63.3:
'I trod the winepress alone.
From all the nations, no one helped me.
I trod them in my anger;
I trampled them in my fury.
Their blood is sprinkled on my garments;
I have stained all my clothing.

63.6:
I trampled the peoples in my anger;
I made them drunk in my fury;
I poured their blood down to the earth.

64.10:
Your holy cities are a wasteland.
Zion is a wilderness;
Jerusalem — a desolation.

65.11:
But you who abandon Yahweh, who forget my holy mountain —
you set a table for Fortune;
you pour out cups of wine for Fate —
